Please note that the NWRCC is not technically subject to the FOI Act. While this means they are not legally obliged to respond to your requests, we have included them in the hope that they choose to voluntarily comply with Freedom of Information.

Name: Office for Learning and Teaching
Notes: The Office for Learning and Teaching Strategic Advisory Committee provides guidance and advice to the Minister to help shape strategic directions of the Office for Learning and Teaching and to set priorities for the grants, fellowships and awards schemes.

Name: Migration Agents Registration Authority
Notes:
As the industry regulator for Australian migration agent services we administer a comprehensive regulatory framework, including relevant provisions of the Act.

This authority is part of the Department of Immigration and Border Protection. Requests are processed by the Department for MARA.

Name: Official Establishments Trust
Notes: Established by the Prime Minister on 20 September 1979 as an independent body to provide advice on the conservation and development of the buildings and grounds of Australia's four official residences: Government House and The Lodge in Canberra and Admiralty House and Kirribilli House in Sydney.

Name: Oil Stewardship Advisory Council
Notes: Section 11 of the Product Stewardship for Oil Act 2000 (the Act) establishes the Oil Stewardship Advisory Council (OSAC). The role of OSAC is to provide the Minister with advice in relation to matters relating to oil recycling, the product stewardship arrangements for oil and the state of the oil industry.

Name: Payments System Board
Notes: The Payments System Board is required to inform the Government of its policies. In the event of a difference of opinion between the Government and the Board, the provisions of the Reserve Bank Act 1959 provide a mechanism for dispute resolution.

Name: PCEHR Independent Advisory Council
Notes: The PCEHR Act established the PCEHR Independent Advisory Council (PCEHR IAC) to advise on the operation and participation in the PCEHR system, clinical, privacy and security matters relating to PCEHR system operations.

Name: PCEHR Jurisdictional Advisory Committee
Notes: The PCEHR Act established the PCEHR Jurisdictional Advisory Committee (PCEHR JAC) to advise the System Operator on matters relating to the interests of the Commonwealth, States and Territories in the PCEHR system.

Name: Prime Minister's Science, Engineering and Innovation Council
Notes: The Prime Minister's Science, Engineering and Innovation Council provides advice to government on scientific and technological developments.

Name: Prime Ministerial Advisory Council on Ex-Service Matters
Notes: The Prime Minister Advisory Council on Ex-Service Matters considers and advises the Prime Minister and Government on strategic and complex matters impacting on the ex-service and defence communities.

Name: Privacy Advisory Committee
Notes: The Privacy Advisory Committee advises the Information Commissioner on privacy issues, and the protection of personal information; provides strategic input to key projects undertaken by the Information Commissioner; fosters collaborative partnerships between key stakeholders to further promote the protection of individual privacy; promotes the value of privacy to the Australian community, business and government; and supports office accountability to external stakeholders.

Name: Product Stewardship Advisory Group
Notes: The Advisory Group's primary role is to provide independent advice to the Minister for use in the development of a list of products proposed to be considered, during the next financial year, as to whether some form of accreditation or regulation under the Product Stewardship Act 2011 might be appropriate. This list must be published by the Minister annually.

Name: Programs Reference Group
Notes: The Programs Reference Group advises the Minister for Health and Ageing and the Agreement Consultative Committee, when such advice is requested, on the policy dimensions of new and continuing Programs under the Fifth Community Pharmacy Agreement.

Name: QUESTACON
Notes:
Questacon – The National Science and Technology Centre and its programs are administered within the Australian Government Department of Industry.
At Questacon, we strive to promote greater understanding and awareness of science and technology within the community. We're committed to making that experience fun, interactive, and relevant.

Name: Refugee Resettlement Advisory Council
Notes: The Refugee Resettlement Advisory Council is a ministerially-appointed expert and independent body that provides advice to the Government on matters relating to the resettlement of refugees and humanitarian entrants in Australia.

Name: Regional Development Australia
Notes: Regional Development Australia (RDA) is an Australian Government initiative that brings together all levels of government to enhance the development of Australia's regions. A national network of RDA committees has been established to achieve this objective.

Name: Small Business Advisory Committee
Notes:
The Small Business Advisory Committee (SBAC) has been established as part of the Government’s Better Regulation Agenda.  The SBAC provides government agencies with greater knowledge and expertise across a wide range of business operations and industry sectors.
The SBAC's role is to improve the quality of regulation and minimise compliance costs for small business by being involved throughout the development of the Regulation Impact Statement process.
In addition, the SBAC provides broad advice to the Government on small business policy matters as well as current and emerging small business issues and trends.
The SBAC operates as a panel, independent from the government, comprising members who have extensive experience with small business.

Name: Statutory Fishing Rights Allocation Review Panel
Notes:
The Statutory Fishing Rights Allocation Review Panel is part of the Agriculture portfolio, and functions in an regulatory, review, inquiry, commission capacity.

The Statutory Fishing Rights Allocation Review Panel reviews certain decisions made by the Australian Fisheries Management Authority

Name: Sydney Airport Community Forum
Notes: The Sydney Airport Community Forum (SACF) advises the Government on noise abatement and related environment issues, providing an important voice for the communities around Sydney Airport. The SACF also allows the community to engage directly with the operators of Sydney Airport as well as Airservices Australia on the Airport’s noise sharing plan.

Name: Teacher Education Ministerial Advisory Group
Notes: The Teacher Education Ministerial Advisory Group has been established to provide advice on how teacher programmes could be improved to better prepare new teachers with the practical skills needed for the classroom.

Name: Threatened Species Scientific Committee
Notes: The Threatened Species Scientific Committee advises the Minister on the amendment and updating of the national lists of threatened species, threatened ecological communities and key threatening processes, together with the making or adoption of recovery plans and threat abatement plans

Name: Tourism Quality Council of Australia
Notes: The Tourism Quality Council of Australia (TQCA) was established to oversee the National Tourism Accreditation Framework (NTAF) and administer T-QUAL Accreditation under Tourism 2020. The TQCA is responsible for overseeing the administration of T-QUAL Accreditation and is the decision maker for granting T-QUAL Accreditation Master Licences to quality assurance schemes such as accreditation programs and Large Tourism Organisations that apply a quality standard to their operations, business units or related business entities. The TQCA is comprised of industry representatives, including an independent Chair, and representatives from the Australian Standing Committee on Tourism (ASCOT), Consumer Affairs Australia New Zealand (CAANZ), Tourism Australia and the Department of Resources, Energy and Tourism.

Name: Tourism Research Australia
Notes: We are Australia's leading provider of quality tourism intelligence across both international and domestic markets. We equip industry with information to strengthen their marketing and business decisions. Our data underpin government tourism policy and help improve the performance of the tourism industry for the benefit of the Australian community.

Name: Tradespersons' Rights Regulation Act Central Committee
Notes: The Tradespersons' Rights Regulation Act Central Committee determine the requirements an applicant must meet in order to be awarded an Australian Recognised Trade Certificate.

Name: Tuition Protection Service
Notes:
The Tuition Protection Service (TPS) is an initiative of the Australian Government to assist international students whose providers are unable to fully deliver their course of study. The TPS ensures that international students are able to either:
	•	complete their studies in another course or with another provider or
	•	receive a refund of their unspent tuition fees.

Name: Uluru-Kata Tjuta Board of Management
Notes: The Uluru-Kata Tjuta Board of Management is established under the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999. The Board manages the park in conjunction with the Director of National Parks. The functions of the Board are to make decisions about management of the park consistent with the park management plan and, in conjunction with the Director, to prepare management plans, monitor the management of the park, and advise the Minister on all future development of the park. The Board has 12 members a majority of whom are indigenous persons nominated by the traditional Aboriginal owners of the park.

Name: Veterans and Veterans Families Counselling Service
Notes:
The VVCS – Veterans and Veterans Families Counselling Service provides counselling and group programs to Australian veterans, peacekeepers and their families. It is a specialised, free and confidential Australia-wide service.
VVCS staff are qualified psychologists or social workers with experience in working with veterans, peacekeepers and their families. They can provide a wide range of treatments and programs for war and service-related mental health conditions including post traumatic stress disorder (PTSD).

Name: Wheat Industry Advisory Taskforce
Notes: The Wheat Industry Advisory Taskforce will examine key issues facing the wheat industry, including availability of stocks information and quality integrity, and provide recommendations to government and industry for their consideration.

Name: Woomera Prohibited Area Advisory Board
Notes: The Woomera Prohibited Area (WPA) Advisory Board monitors and reports on the balance of national security and economic interests in the WPA; oversees the implementation of the co-existence policy arrangements; and fosters strategic relationships between Defence and non-Defence users of the WPA

Name: Deputy Prime Minister
Notes: Requests for personal documents, documents of a party political nature, or documents held in the prime minister's capacity as a local member of parliament are likely to be refused. See the Information Commissioner guidelines for more details.

Name: CRC for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health
Notes: The CRC for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health will address the key challenge of closing the health gap. This challenge will involve: research focused on child and maternal health, reducing chronic illness risk across the life-course, and improving early intervention and chronic illness management; research focused on the capacity of local communities and organisations to develop interventions that address the determinants of health across a range of local sectors and settings; and research enabling the reform of policy and programs, workforce development, and whole-of-government approaches to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Advanced Composite Structures
Notes: The CRC for Advanced Composite Structures (CRC-ACS) is addressing the major challenge of embedding Australian composites industry small and medium enterprises (SMEs) into global supply chains. It is achieving this through collaborative engagement to attract multinational businesses, undertake collaborative research with Australian researchers and enterprises, and build reliance on Australia’s proven capability for major technological advancement. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Advanced Manufacturing CRC
Notes: The major challenge of the Advanced Manufacturing CRC (AMCRC) is to create valuable Australian owned intellectual property in the areas of advanced materials and next generation manufacturing processes. The CRC also aims to develop the capability to assist Australian manufacturing to transition from a traditional manufacturing to a knowledge-based advanced manufacturing industry. The AMCRC is assisting the Australian manufacturing SME sector via INNOVATIVITY®, AMCRC’s Innovation Management program. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Alertness, Safety and Productivity
Notes: The CRC for Alertness, Safety and Productivity is dedicated to reducing the avoidable burden of poor alertness on the safety, productivity and health of all Australians. The CRC will develop new tools and products to improve alertness, increase productivity and enhance safety. The major challenge addressed by the CRC for Alertness, Safety and Productivity is to boost productivity and lower health system costs by reducing the incidence of motor vehicle and workplace accidents and errors. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Antarctic Climate and Ecosystems CRC
Notes: The Antarctic Climate and Ecosystems CRC (ACE CRC) is investigating the critical scientific uncertainties, highlighted by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, that limit Australia’s and the global community’s ability to respond effectively to climate change. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Australian Seafood CRC
Notes: The Australian Seafood CRC’s research and innovation challenge centres on the seafood value chain - from wild harvest or from aquaculture production, right to the consumer. The Seafood CRC assists the seafood industry to profitably deliver safe, high-quality, nutritious Australian seafood products to premium markets, domestically and overseas. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Automotive Australia 2020 CRC
Notes: AutoCRC’s research is structured around three research programs: Vehicle Electrification Gaseous Fuels Sustainable Automotive Manufacturing Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Bushfire CRC
Notes: The Bushfire CRC is conducting research to understand the underlying risk exposure of the broad Australasian community and the things it values; the communication of risk and threat; and management issues related to extreme fire events. The research builds upon the broad outputs of the earlier Bushfire CRC program, which began in 2003, to help the emergency management sector and the community to address the many challenges produced by fire and other natural disasters.  Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC
Notes: The purpose and mission of the Bushfire and Natural Hazards CRC (BNHCRC) is to conduct end-user inspired, high-quality applied research to: Reduce the risks from bushfire and natural hazards Reduce the social, economic and environmental costs of disasters Contribute to the national disaster resilience agenda Build internationally renowned Australian research capacity and capability Enable Australian small to medium enterprises to be innovative in natural hazard products and services Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Biomarker Translation
Notes: The overall aim of the CRC for Biomarker Translation is to develop antibodies directed against therapeutic and diagnostic targets (biomarkers) present on cells that play a key role in major diseases, including autoimmune disease (especially rheumatoid arthritis) and cancers (haematological, colorectal, breast and prostate) Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Cancer Therapeutics
Notes: The major challenge for the CRC for Cancer Therapeutics (CTx) is to address the leading single cause of death in Australia – cancer. CTx discovers, protects and develops small molecules into pre-clinical drug candidates with high commercial potential. These candidates are chosen for their ability to better target cancer cells rather than normal healthy cells, to improve clinical outcomes and produce large healthcare system efficiencies.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Capital Markets CRC
Notes: The Capital Markets CRC conducts applied research, the objective of which is to enhance capital and insurance markets integrity and efficiency. The two main areas where Capital Markets CRC is making a profound difference are in the security markets and health and accident compensation insurance markets where its technologies are the market leaders. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Cell Therapy Manufacturing
Notes: The CRC for Cell Therapy Manufacturing will bring together materials scientists, cell biologists, bioprocess engineers, clinicians and industry to increase the affordability and accessibility of cell therapies and position Australia in the vanguard of cell therapy manufacture. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Contamination Assessment and Remediation of the Environment
Notes: The CRC for Contamination Assessment and Remediation of the Environment’s (CRC CARE) key challenge is to achieve a paradigm shift in the Australian remediation industry. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Dairy Futures CRC
Notes: The Dairy Futures CRC will directly address the major dairy industry challenge – a return to 2% total factor productivity gains that drove the expansion of the industry through the 1980s and 1990s. Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Deep Exploration Technologies CRC
Notes: Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it   The Deep Exploration Technologies CRC (DET CRC) was established to address the most significant challenge to the future of the minerals industry in Australia, i.e. the reduction in the mineral resources inventory due to high production rates and low mineral exploration success.

Name: Energy Pipelines CRC
Notes: The major challenge to be tackled by the Energy Pipelines CRC is to provide the Australian energy pipeline industry with the technology necessary to extend the life of the existing ageing natural gas transmission network, and to build the new networks necessary to support increased demand for natural gas, and the transmission of the new energy cycle fluid hydrogen and carbon dioxide.  Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Future Farm Industries CRC
Notes: The research and focus of Future Farm Industries CRC Ltd (FFI CRC) is the development of innovative farming systems and new perennial plant species and cultivars (Profitable Perennials™ technologies) that improve productivity through effective water use and maintaining ground cover while enhancing natural resource values. FFI CRC’s goal is to have Profitable Perennials™ adopted on 7.5 million hectares or 13% of southern Australian farmlands by 2030. These technologies will become the foundation for future livestock and cropping enterprises augmented by new biomass production to the benefit of farms, regions and landscapes.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Greenhouse Gas Technologies
Notes: The CRC for Greenhouse Gas Technologies (CO2CRC) undertakes the following research programs: Understanding storage resources Making CCS costeffective Facilitating deployment of CCS  Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: The HEARing CRC
Notes: The HEARing CRC is focused on the twin challenges of more effective prevention and improved remediation of hearing loss. Hearing loss affects one in six Australians, with a total financial cost estimated to be around $A23 billion per annum. Through research and its utilisation, the HEARing CRC aims to reduce the impact of hearing loss by: maximising lifelong hearing retention; reducing loss of productivity due to hearing loss; increasing uptake and use of hearing technology; and providing postgraduate and professional and training.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for High Integrity Australian Pork
Notes: The CRC for High Integrity Australian Pork undertakes the following research programs: Confinement-free sow and piglet management Herd health management Healthy pork consumption Carbon conscious nutrient inputs and outputs Improving sow reproduction Nutritional manipulations to enhance the performance and feed efficiency of growing pigs   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Invasive Animals CRC
Notes: The Invasive Animals Cooperative Research Centre (IA CRC) aims to counteract the environmental, social and economic impacts of invasive animals, through the development and application of new technologies and by integration of strategic pest management approaches across agencies and jurisdictions. Research programs focus on reducing the impacts of rabbits, wild dogs and rodent damage and impacts and rates of spread of carp and other pest fish species. IA CRC aims to increase agricultural profitability through improved integration of existing biological, conventional and newly developed control options for invasive animals and to protect biodiversity.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Living with Autism Spectrum Disorder
Notes: The CRC for Living with Autism Spectrum Disorders will undertake highly innovative research to directly improve the lifetime prospects of Australian individuals with ASD, provide much needed guidance, support and direction for their families, and enable medical practitioners, educators, therapists, support workers and employers to work effectively with people with ASD.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Low Carbon Living
Notes: The aim of the CRC for Low Carbon Living is to provide government and industry with technological and policy tools to overcome identified market barriers preventing adoption of cost effective low carbon products and services, while maintaining industry competitiveness and improving quality of life.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Mental Health
Notes: The CRC for Mental Health undertakes research to identify and validate biomarkers for the early detection and treatment of neurodegenerative disorders and psychoses. We then work with our partner end users to ensure that new techniques and approaches are integrated into medical and health care practice.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC Mining
Notes: CRCMining’s challenge is to reduce energy consumption at all stages of mining. Mining is a significant consumer of energy, accounting for 4.7% of Australia’s primary energy, and 13.8% of CO2-equivalent emissions. CRCMining’s activities will focus on technologies associated with mining processes – in rock fragmentation, digging and transport. Automation of technologies will deliver benefits by improving the efficiency of digging and haulage and by providing improved ore grade control at the point of excavation.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Optimising Resource Extraction
Notes: The CRC for Optimising Resource Extraction (CRC ORE) is facilitating a transformation of the methods used by Australia’s mining and minerals industry to evaluate and extract mineral deposits. This will include the capability to comprehensively characterise, model and evaluate the economic and environmental impact of improved mineral-extraction methods.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Oral Health CRC
Notes: The Oral Health CRC will address the substantial national economic ($A6.7 billion per annum) and social burden of oral diseases and disorders. New areas of research will involve biomarkers of disease, the development of early diagnostics, new preventive strategies and products and oral health promotion programs, minimal intervention treatment approaches, novel dental professional products and novel reconstruction and regenerative approaches for the replacement of lost tissue and function.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Plant Biosecurity CRC
Notes: The Plant Biosecurity CRC (PBCRC) aims to develop and deploy knowledge and tools to provide the scientific support essential for safeguarding Australia from the economic, environmental and social consequences of damaging pest incursions.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Polymers
Notes: The major challenge addressed by the CRC for Polymers is to establish Australian manufacturing as a leading provider and exporter of products that meet emerging global needs in three areas - health therapies and delivery, water and food security, and low-cost solar energy - using enabling and sustainable advanced polymer technology.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Poultry CRC
Notes: The Poultry CRC’s major challenge is to help Australia achieve sustainable, ethical poultry production in the face of population growth and climate change.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Rail Innovation
Notes: The CRC for Rail Innovation is leading the way in research and development for the future of Australia’s railways. The CRC has managed over 100 research projects spanning across the research themes of Safety and Security; Performance; Climate Change and the Environment; Workforce Development; Smart Technology and Urban Rail Access.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Remote Economic Participation
Notes: The CRC for Remote Economic Participation (CRC-REP) is a public good research centre which delivers solutions that address social and economic disadvantage in remote Australia. This challenge is proving to be intractable despite significant current investments and it involves the complex interplay of economic, environmental and societal factors.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Sheep Industry Innovation
Notes: The CRC for Sheep Industry Innovation was established to deliver transformational change in the sheep industry. The main challenge was to improve productivity, produce sheep that are easier to manage and improve meat quality through increasing the rate of genetic change and introduction of genomic technologies for breeding programs. The CRC’s Information Nucleus program has been a huge success in delivering on these ambitious objectives.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Smart Services CRC
Notes: Smart Services CRC creates new and improved services for industry to enable customers to receive affordably and easily personalised, continuous service from businesses, irrespective of their world-wide location, and which instantly adjusts for any mobile or fixed device they use.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Spatial Information
The Vision CRC
Notes: The Vision CRC will address the major challenges of significant vision impairment and eye health issues by solving problems related to ocular and contact lens discomfort; elimination of presbyopia and cataract through the use of biocompatible implant materials for permanent vision correction; slowing the progress of myopia; improved skills and knowledge for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander health workers; integrated models of vision care delivery for remote and indigenous communities, and development of an intelligent retinal camera for rapid detection of blinding eye disease.  Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: CRC for Water Sensitive Cities
Notes: The CRC for Water Sensitive Cities brings together the inter-disciplinary research expertise and thought-leadership to undertake research that will revolutionise water management in Australia and overseas. In collaboration with over 70 research, industry and government partners, we will deliver the socio-technical urban water management solutions, and training programs, and industry engagement required to make towns and cities water sensitive.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Wound Management Innovation CRC
Notes: The Wound Management Innovation CRC will examine key challenges in improving wound healing to provide quality-of-life for people with wounds, and cost-effective wound care that lessens the burden on the health system. The CRC will address the molecular and biological mechanisms that underlie wound healing, leading to the identification of therapeutic targets and biomarkers for creating novel diagnostic and prognostic tools and therapeutic solutions. The CRC will develop innovative tools, diagnostics and therapeutics for the next generation of advanced wound management solutions, including ‘smart dressings’ that incorporate biosensors to monitor wound healing and materials to release therapeutic compounds. The CRC will also deliver improved wound management through the evaluation and implementation of evidence-based wound care, new preventative and treatment strategies and improved clinical care pathways.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Young and Well CRC
Notes: The Young and Well CRC unites young people with researchers, practitioners, innovators and policymakers from over 75 partners. Together, we explore the role of technology in young people’s lives, and how it can be used to improve the mental health and wellbeing of young people aged 12 to 25. The Young and Well CRC is investigating and building supportive online tools and environments to promote young people’s wellbeing and safety online; utilising technologies as facilitators of good mental health for vulnerable young people; and developing innovative services for those experiencing mental health difficulties. Expected impacts include a reduction in youth suicide, suicide attempts and self-harm; a reduction in depression, anxiety, substance use and social isolation; and an improvement in quality of life for young people, their families and their communities.   Please note: This authority is not technically subject to FOI, but you can still make requests to it

Name: Assistant Minister for Infrastructure and Regional Development
Notes: Requests for personal documents, documents of a party political nature, or documents held in the minister’s capacity as a local member of parliament are likely to be refused. Name: Australian Grape and Wine Authority
Notes: The Australian Grape and Wine Authority (AGWA) is the single Australian Government statutory service body for the Australian grape and wine community. We commenced on 1 July 2014 under the Act, which merged the RD&E activities of the Grape and Wine Research and Development Corporation and the market development and regulatory activities of Wine Australia Corporation in one body. We conduct many of our activities under our trading name Wine Australia. This is our long-established brand for our market development activities, and our sector stakeholders have strongly supported the use of ‘Wine Australia’.

Name: Office of Township Leasing
Notes:
The Office of the Executive Director was established by the Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Amendment (Township Leasing) Act 2007 and came into effect on 1 July 2007. Under the Act the Executive Director is a statutory office holder and is appointed by the Governor-General for a period not exceeding five years.
The functions of the Executive Director are to:
enter into Township Leases on behalf of the Commonwealth
administer Township Leases, including administering subleases, and
manage other rights and interests derived from Township Leases.

Notes: Requests for personal documents, documents of a party political nature, or documents held in the minister’s capacity as a local member of parliament are likely to be refused. Name: Road Safety Remuneration Tribunal
Notes: The Road Safety Remuneration Tribunal (RSRT) is an independent national tribunal that has functions relating to the road transport industry.

Name: Royal Australian Air Force Welfare Trust Fund
Notes: The Royal Australian Air Force Welfare Trust Fund is part of the Defence portfolio, and functions in an executive management capacity.

Name: Workplace Gender Equality Agency
Notes:
The Workplace Gender Equality Agency is an Australian Government statutory agency created by the Workplace Gender Equality Act 2012.
The Agency is charged with promoting and improving gender equality in Australian workplaces.

Name: Wreck Bay Aboriginal Community Council
Notes: WBACC administers the ownership and management of the land and waters within the Jervis Bay Territory and represents community interests. Established by the Aboriginal Land Grant (Jervis Bay Territory) Act 1986 to hold title to land and provide council services to the Aboriginal community of Jervis Bay.

Name: National Measurement Institute
Tags: industry_and_science oaic_report_2011_2012 directory_gov_au minister foi_yes federal
Notes: NMI is the peak Australian measurement body responsible for biological, chemical, legal, physical and trade measurement.

Name: Capital Metro Agency
Notes: The Capital Metro Agency has responsibility for the design, procurement and delivery of a light rail service between Gungahlin and the City.

Name: ACT Chief Minister, Treasury And Economic Development Directorate
Notes: CMTEDD leads the ACT Public Service (ACTPS) and provides strategic advice and support to the Chief Minister, Treasurer, Minister for Economic Development and the Cabinet on policy, financial and economic matters, service delivery and whole of government issues.

Name: ACT Community Services Directorate
Notes: The Community Services Directorate has the responsibility for a wide range of human services functions in the ACT, including multicultural and community affairs, public and community housing services and policy, children, youth and family support services and policy, disability policy and services, therapy services, Child and Family Centres, the ACT Government Concessions Program, homelessness and community services.

Name: ACT Economic Development Directorate
Notes: The Economic Development Directorate facilitates the Territory's economic prosperity in line with the Government's commitment to sustainable development.

Name: ACT Education And Training Directorate
Notes: The Directorate identifies education and training priorities and the development of strategies, policies and planning for improved learning outcomes through government schools. The Directorate registers non government schools; and administers vocational education and training in the ACT.

Name: ACT Environment And Planning Directorate
Notes:
The Environment and Planning Directorate promotes sustainable living and resource use, strengthens the Territory‚Äôs response to climate change, and provides a planning and land use system that contributes to the sustainable development of the ACT.

The Directorate‚Äôs aim is to lead the Territory in developing and implementing targeted policies and programs that address environment protection and sustainability, nature conservation, heritage, water and energy security, sustainable urban design, and sustainable transport and spatial planning.

Name: ACT Health Directorate
Notes: In collaboration with all stakeholders, the Directorate establishes direction through the identification of priorities, and the development of strategies, policies and planning for improved health outcomes.

Name: ACT Justice And Community Safety Directorate
Notes: The ACT Justice and Community Safety Directorate comprises several agencies and is responsible for a wide range of activities and services in the areas of justice, the law, emergencies, commercial practices and government elections.

Name: ACT Territory And Municipal Services Directorate
Notes: The Territory and Municipal Services Directorate (TAMS) delivers a wide range of services including collecting recycling and rubbish, running public libraries and ensuring municipal infrastructure such as streetlights and public barbeques are in good working order.

Name: Canberra Institute Of Technology
Notes: Canberra Institute of Technology (CIT) is the ACT and region's leading training organisation providing career opportunities and partnering with industry and individuals to develop a skilled community.

Name: ACT Audit Office
Notes: The Office of the Auditor-General is responsible for undertaking independent audits of management performance and the financial statements of public sector bodies.

Name: ACT Building And Construction Industry Training Fund Authority
Notes: The ACT Building and  Construction Industry Training Fund Authority provides training grants to industry workers to improve existing skills and to develop new skills.

Name: ACT Electoral Commission
Notes: The ACT Electoral Commission is an independent Statutory Authority with the responsibility for the conduct of Elections and Referendums for the ACT Legislative Assembly and for the provision of electoral advice to a wide range of clients.

Name: ACT Long Service Leave Authority
Notes: The ACT Long Service Leave Authority administers portable long service leave schemes for the construction, cleaning and community sector industries under ACT Government legislation.

Name: ACT Teacher Quality Institute
Notes: The ACT Teacher Quality Institute (TQI) was established by the ACT Government under the 'ACT Teacher Quality Institute Act 2010' to raise the standing of the teaching profession in the ACT and to strengthen the quality and sustainability of the teaching workforce.

Name: ACTEW Corporation Limited
Notes:
ACTEW Corporation Limited (ACTEW) is a government owned company with assets and investments in water, wastewater, electricity, gas and telecommunications totalling $1.4b.

ACTEW owns the water and wastewater assets and business in the ACT, is a 50% owner, with Singapore Power International and AGL Energy Limited, of ActewAGL and holds an 18% investment in TransACT Communications Pty Limited.

ACTEW was corporatised on 1 July 1995 and has reporting and compliance obligations under the Corporations Act 2001 and other legislation. It has three wholly owned subsidiary companies:

ACTEW Distribution Limited
ACTEW Retail Limited
ACTEW China Pty Limited
ACTEW Distribution and ACTEW Retail are ACTEW partnership companies in the ActewAGL Distribution and Retail partnerships. ACTEW Distribution Limited is also a joint owner of Ecowise Environmental Pty Limited, Australia largest single provider of integrated environmental analytical, monitoring and consulting services. ACTEW China holds business investments in the Peoples Republic of China.

The Company has two voting shareholders, the Chief Minister and Deputy Chief Minister of the ACT.

Name: ACTEWAGL
Notes: ActewAGL formed in October 2000 when the Australian Gas Light Company (AGL), a major private sector group, and ACTEW Corporation, a government-owned enterprise, entered into Australia's first utility joint venture. Ownership of ActewAGL is shared equally between AGL and ACTEW Corporation.

Name: ACT Cultural Facilities Corporation
Notes: The Cultural Facilities Corporation is an ACT Government statutory authority established under the Cultural Facilities Corporation ACT (1997), to manage significant cultural venues in Canberra:

Name: ACT Exhibition Park Corporation
Notes:
Welcome to Exhibition Park In Canberra (EPIC) - the National Capital's premier multi-purpose events complex.

The ambient country setting, versatility and personalised service set the venue apart from any other.

EPIC is located just 8 minutes north of the city centre and its geographic proximity to Sydney and Melbourne make it easily accessible for interstate travellers. Canberra Airport is only a 15 minute drive away and public transport services operate to and from the venue's main entrance.

Name: ACT Independent Competition And Regulatory Commission
ACT Regional Development Australia
Notes: Regional Development Australia is a national network of committees fostering regional economic development. There are 55 RDA Committees which work with all three tiers of government, regional business and the wider community to boost the economic capability and performance of their region.

Name: ACT Office of the Under Treasurer
Notes: The Office of the Under Treasurer directly supports the Under Treasurer with advice on matters of policy and corporate strategy. It also provides executive and administrative assistance to the Under Treasurer and Ministerial liaison functions with the Treasurer‚Äôs Office

Name: ACT Insurance Authority
Notes:
The ACT Insurance Authority (ACTIA) is a statutory authority established by the ACT Government.
ACTIA's role is to manage the self-insurance arrangements of the ACT Government. As a captive insurer, ACTIA provides a full range of general insurance coverage for ACT Government directorates and agencies.

Name: ACT Territory Records Office
Notes: Territory Records Office: The Territory Records Office is responsible for the implementation of the Territory Records Act 2002 within Territory agencies, and the production of standards and guidelines to assist agencies to meet their legislative requirements for recordkeeping. The TRO also delivers Archives ACT, the public face of records management, and the community access point to older ACT Government records.

Name: ACT Workplace Safety And Industrial Relations
Notes:
The Workplace Safety and Industrial Relations Division provides a range of services to the ACT government, community and industry including:
‚Ä¢

Name: Housing And Community Services ACT
Home page: http://www.dhcs.act.gov.au/hcs/default.htm" TARGET="_top">Community Services Directorate HomepageImage/Map
Notes:
Housing ACT provides information on housing assistance options - public, private, and community based and emergency/crisis housing. Assesses the eligibility for and allocates public rental properties, Manages rental tenancies and tenant accounts. Assesses and provides rental assistance to public housing tenants (rental rebates). Manages the Customer Assistance Help line (complaints tenants may have in relation to ACT Housing's service or work).

Community Development manages public housing assets as the nominated owner for the territory, including acquisition, disposal, redevelopment and repair, maintenance and improvement of those assets. It also develops and manages Housing Policy and community housing. Community Services provides Supported Accommodation Assistance Program, a program for homelessness, and purchasing and policy also in relation to a range of community services - Including emergency relief, crisis counselling services and community development programs. Administers the ACT Concessions program.

Name: ACT Office For Children, Youth And Family Support
Notes: The Office for Children, Youth and Family Support works in partnership with the community to provide care and protection services to children and young people, and family and community support to meet the needs of the people of the ACT. The Office also operates a forty bed youth detention centre and supervises young people who have been placed on a court order.

Name: ACT Public Housing Renewal Taskforce
Notes:
The Public Housing Renewal Taskforce (Taskforce) has responsibility for the management, redevelopment and delivery of the following program of works:

Individual replacement projects for the public housing property portfolio on the Northbourne Avenue corridor

Program of accelerated renewal for the Public Housing portfolio including the redevelopment of Multi-Unit Properties

Asset Recycling Initiative ‚Äì proposed program of asset sales and infrastructure investment

Omnibus Territory Plan Variations

The Taskforce comprises staff from the Community Services Directorate and the Chief Minister, Treasury and Economic Development Directorate.

Name: Therapy ACT
Notes: Therapy ACT provides a multidisciplinary therapy and support service for children, with developmental delays from birth to 8 years and people with developmental disabilities aged from birth to 65 years of age, including assistance with physical, intellectual, communication and other functional difficulties. It also provides an autism assessment service. Therapy and support services are available for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech pathology, social work and psychology.

Name: ACT Gambling And Racing Commission
Notes: Controls, supervises and regulates gaming in the ACT including: gaming machines, lotteries, interactive gaming, casino, racing and wagering. The Commission collects relevant fees and taxes and monitors and researches social impacts of gambling.

Name: ACT Office For Schools
Notes: To work closely with schools supporting them to develop sustainable processes that ensure a culture of school improvement and accountability related to their individual context.

Name: ACT Office of the Surveyor-General and Land Information
Notes:
The Office of the Surveyor-General regulates surveying and registers surveyors in the ACT. It maintains the Territory's survey control infrastructure and is the verifying authority for length in the ACT. It provides advice to surveyors and examines survey plans for compliance with the Surveyors Act and the Districts Act.
The Office of the Surveyor-General also allocates and maintains street addresses, place names including road and division names, and the Government's spatial information about blocks, sections, districts, divisions, street addresses, electoral divisions, land tenure, roads, open space, national land, elevations including contours, community facilities, building footprints and water bodies.

Name: ACT Office of the Commissioner for Sustainability and the Environment
Notes: The functions of the Office of the Commissioner for Sustainability and the Environment are to produce State of Environment Reports for the ACT, to investigate complaints from the community, regarding the management of the environment by the ACT Government and/or its Agencies, to conduct investigations into actions of an Agency, where those actions would have a substantial impact on the environment of the ACT, and to make recommendations for consideration by Government and include in her annual report the outcomes of those recommendations.

Name: ACT Canberra Hospital Foundation
Notes: This office is responsible for the coordination of Canberra Hospital fundraising activities. This includes the development of fundraising events and opportunities; receipt and processing of donations; and the development of appropriate policies and procedures.

Name: ACT Health Protection Service
Notes: Responsible for public health protection in the ACT, including minimising the impact of communicable diseases, developing immunisation policies and investigating health complaints relating to public premises such as restaurants, swimming pools, boarding houses and skin penetration facilities. The service comprises the ACT Government Analytical Laboratory, Communicable Diseases Control, Immunisation, Pharmaceutical Services, Radiation Safety and Environmental Health.

Name: ACT Office of the Chief Health Officer
ACT Hospice - Clare Holland House
Notes:
The ACT Hospice, situated on the shores of the lake, East Basin, is conducted as part of Calvary Public Hospital. It is funded by the ACT Health Directorate.

The mission and commitment of Hospice staff is to work together as an inter-disciplinary team, where skill and compassionate care emphasise the quality of life for each person. Staff at the Hospice work together making every effort to try to meet all the needs; physical, emotional, spiritual and social, of each patient and their family.

Name: ACT Canberra Hospital And Health Services
ACT Community Health
Notes: Community Health is the major provider of community-based health in the Australian Capital Territory. We aim to be the catalyst transforming and revitalising health services in the ACT.

Name: Public Trustee For The ACT
Notes: The Public Trustee for the ACT is an ACT government statutory office established to provide the following services to the ACT community: Preparation of Wills where the Public Trustee is named as the executor or co-executor; Administration of deceased estates under Will or Intestacy; Trustee for life interest estates and persons lacking legal capacity; Financial management under Enduring Power of Attorney and under Order of the ACT Civil and Administrative Tribunal (ACAT), or under Power of Attorney; Examination of accounts for external managers under the Guardianship and Management or Property Act 1991; or under Power of Attorney; Asset services to government in relation to Confiscation of Criminal Assets; Safe custody services for established clients; Unclaimed money; Investment services for ACT government trust funds; Trustee for GreaterGood, the Capital Region Community Foundation.

Name: Public Advocate Of The ACT
Notes: The Public Advocate of the ACT's Vision is for a caring community where the rights and interests of vulnerable people are protected. The PA ACT undertakes Guardianship and Advocacy functions, as well as MAP and CCO.

Name: Ombudsman Of The ACT
Notes: The Ombudsman considers and investigates complaints from people who believe they have been treated unfairly or unreasonably by an ACT Government directorate or agency, including the Australian Federal Police in their community policing role.

Name: ACT Legal Aid Commission
Notes: The Legal Aid Commission (ACT) is an independent statutory authority established under the Legal Aid Act 1977 (the Act) and its role is to provide legal assistance in the Australian Capital Territory in accordance with the Act.

Name: ACT Human Rights Commission
Notes:
The Human Rights Commission (HRC) is an independent statutory agency comprised of:
* Children & Young People Commissioner
* Disability & Community Services Commissioner
* Health Services Commissioner
* Human Rights & Discrimination Commissioner

The HRC investigates and resolves complaints about:
* Discrimination and sexual harassment
* Health services
* Disability services
* Services for children and young people
* Services for older people

The HRC also undertakes a range of other activities, including:
* Training on human rights and discrimination
* Community education and outreach activities
* Advice and recommendations on legislation, policies and services affecting vulnerable groups in the community
* Facilitating service improvement
* Promoting community awareness of human rights

Name: ACT Human Rights And Discrimination Commissioner
Notes:
The Human Rights and Discrimination Commission investigates and resolves complaints about unlawful discrimination and harassment that occurs in an area of public life.

People can make a complaint if they feel they have been treated unfavourably because of their:
* sex
* sexuality
* transsexuality
* relationship status
* status as a parent or carer
* pregnancy
* breastfeeding
* race
* religious or political conviction
* disability
* guide dog or other assistance animal
* membership (or non-membership) of an association of employers or employees
* age
* profession, trade, occupation or calling
* spent criminal conviction
* association with a person who has an attribute listed above

A complaint can be made if the unfair treatment occurred in the context of:
* employment (including recruitment and job agencies)
* provision of goods, services or facilities
* education
* access to public buildings
* accommodation
* clubs

Name: ACT Health Services Commissioner
Notes:
The Health Services Commissioner investigates and resolves complaints about:
* Health services
* Services for older people

Name: ACT Disability And Community Services Commissioner
Notes:
The Disability and Community Services Commissioner investigates and resolves complaints about disability services in the ACT, including:
* Residential care
* Respite care
* Home based care
* Support & advocacy services
* Rehabilitation services
* Equipment services
* Services for carers

Name: ACT Children And Young People Commissioner
Notes:
The Children and Young People Commissioner (CYPC) has a number of roles, including:
-Consulting with young people
-Resolving complaints and concerns about services for children and young people
-providing advice to government and community organisations about how to improve children and young people services.

Put simply, the role of the CYPC is to help make Canberra a better place for children and young people.

Name: ACT Federal Privacy Commission
Notes: The Privacy Commissioner is responsible for administering the Privacy Act 1988 (Cth) and is a member of the Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission.

Name: ACT Director Of Public Prosecution
Notes: Also known as the DPP.

Name: ACT Parliamentary Counsel's Office
Notes: The office drafts legislation for the ACT Government, individual members of the Legislative Assembly and ACT courts. The office also arranges for the printing of ACT bills and subordinate legislation, prepares republications and annual volumes of ACT legislation, tables and other information about ACT legislation, and makes them available in printed and electronic form.

Name: ACT Law Courts And Tribunal Administration
Notes: Section Contact Numbers - Civil 6207 1709, Criminal 6207 1728, ACAT Tribunal 6207 1740, Childrens Court 6207 1746, Listings / Transcripts 6207 1390, Protection Orders 6207 1713, Coroners Court 6207 1754, Administration 6207 1737.

Name: ACT Civil And Administrative Tribunal
Notes:
The ACT Civil and Administrative Tribunal provides a way of resolving disputes quickly and fairly in the ACT. The Tribunal has power to resolve and determine applications about:

* reviews of administrative functions;
* discrimination complaints;
* guardianship, financial management and enduring powers of attorney;
* mental health treatment and care;
* residential tenancies disputes;
* energy and water hardship and complaints;
* civil disputes valued at under $10,000;
* unit titles disputes;
* liquor licensing;
* compliance with some long service leave obligations;
* discipline of various occupations including construction occupations, surveyors, architects, security agents, real estate agents, and the health and legal professions.

Name: ACT Court Assistance And Referral Service
Notes: Community based support service for those charged with offences in the ACT law courts, witnesses and relatives and friends. This service does not provide legal advice.

Name: ACT Corrective Services
Notes: ACT Corrective Services is responsible for providing a range of adult and youth correctional services to the community. This includes monitoring offenders compliance with court orders, assisting offenders to address offending behavior and monitoring the care and safety of persons held in custody.

Name: ACT Government Solicitor
Notes: The ACT Government Solicitor provides legal advice and representation to the Territory, its Ministers and agencies.

Name: ACT Roads And Public Transport Division
Notes: Roads and Public Transport administer many aspects of transport for the Territory including public transport services (ACTION) and infrastructure management, including roads, bridges and stormwater.

Name: ACT Parks And City Services Division
Notes: The Parks and Conservation Service, City Services and Libraries make up the Parks and City Services Business Group. It regulates environmental activities using compliance and licensing frameworks that help protect and preserve our natural and cultural values. It is also responsible for biosecurity, managing Canberra's extensive parks, nature reserves and open places, domestic animal services and public libraries.

Name: Tidbinbilla Nature Reserve
Notes: Tidbinbilla Nature Reserve is located on Paddys River Road via Point Hut Crossing (Gordon) or via the Cotter Road (Stromlo).

Name: ACT National Arboretum Canberra
Notes: The National Arboretum Canberra was formerly known as the Canberra International Arboretum and Gardens.

Name: Libraries ACT
Notes: Provision of public library services for ACT residents, and the collection and dissemination of historical information about the ACT and region through the ACT Heritage Library.

Name: ACT Heritage Library
Notes:
The ACT Heritage Library helps tell the stories of Canberra and its people. The Heritage Library collects, preserves, promotes and provides access to the documents that record the lives of Canberrans at home and in the wider community.
Materials include books, maps, photographs, manuscripts, journals, records of local organisations and individuals and ephemera.
Services include local history reference services.

Name: ACT City Services
Notes:
City Services is responsible for a range of core municipal and Territory services, which include the key operational areas and functions are:
  • Licensing and Compliance (policy, guidelines and licensing for use of public land and under the Nature Conservation Act, Fisheries Act and Lakes Act, City Rangers performing regulatory/compliance functions, tree protection, domestic animals regulation, welfare services and biosecurity);
  • Place Management (city-wide cleaning and open space asset maintenance including mowing, playground, picnic and associated infrastructure maintenance, care of lakes and waterways and delivery of horticultural displays for Floriade);
  • Urban Treescapes (urban tree planning, management and maintenance);
  • Asset Data and integration (Provide divisional support in relation to asset data management, GIS mapping and are the "interface" between PATS operational areas and TAMS AIB, AA, INTACT, Canberra Connect, ACTPLA etc for ICT, systems and data related activities).

Name: Capital Woodland And Wetlands Conservation Trust
Access Canberra
Notes:
Access Canberra provides information, payments, services and emergency support to the ACT community on behalf of ACT Government agencies. Access Canberra is known through its service operations - Access Canberra Shopfronts, Access Canberra Contact Centre (13 22 81), and Access Canberra online. In addition, Access Canberra also supports whole of government arrangements for Australia Post BillPay, BPay and eLockbox.

FOI requests relating to Access Canberra are sent to the Chief Minister, Treasury and Economic Development Directorate.

Name: ACT Yarralumla Nursery
Notes: This unit grows and supplies plant material for ACT Government landscape development projects, PCL and the ACT Government plant issue scheme. The Nursery also sells plant materials to local landscape contractors, retails locally sourced and grown plants through the Nursery Garden Gentre: and undertakes contract growing for the Nursery industry, Greening Australia, hobby farmers, rural land owners, district councils and government directorates.

Name: Capital Linen Service
Notes: Capital Linen Service provides linen rental and laundering services to a wide range of clients in the ACT region. Its clients include public and private hospitals and health facilities as well as hotels and restaurants in the hospitality industry in Canberra. It employs over 100 people at its laundry in Mitchell.

Name: ACT Canberra Cemeteries
Notes: The ACT Public Cemeteries Authority manages Woden, Gungahlin and Hall cemeteries. It is a financially separate business unit of TAMS. The Directorate supports the Chief Executive Officer of the ACT Public Cemeteries Authority and the Minister for Territory and Municipal Services as part of the Cemeteries and Crematoria Act 2003 and a Memorandum of Understanding exists between the Directorate and the Authority.

Name: ACT Nowaste
Notes: ACT NOWaste's role is to implement the ACT Government's No Waste Strategy through effective programs that engage the community and encourage sustainable waste minimisation and management practices. ACT NOWaste facilitates and encourages the resource recovery industry to maximise the recovery and recycling of wastes in the ACT and surrounding region. Other responsibilities include provision of domestic garbage and recyclables collection services, sorting and reprocessing of recyclable materials, and management of waste acceptance and disposal facilities.

Name: Roads ACT
Notes: Roads ACT is a business within Territory and Municipal Services (TAMS) with responsibility for the management, use and maintenance of the ACT roads, bridges, footpaths, traffic lights, street lighting and the stormwater infrastructure asset base. Roads develop a sizeable capital works program each year and are responsible for the management of Canberra's traffic. Roads also provide line-marking, project management, sign design and manufacture and respond to emergency works that is underpinned by a 24 hour service.

A public university, recognised and funded by the Commonwealth Government, ACU is open to students and staff of all beliefs.

The Office of the National Rail Safety Regulator (ONRSR) is an independent body corporate established under the Rail Safety National Law (South Australia) Act 2012.

The primary objectives of the ONRSR are to encourage and enforce safe railway operations and to promote and improve national rail safety.
